entry.title: Android: Remove occurrences of JavaRef<jclass>
entry.content:
jclass objects should always come JNI Zero's from generated _clazz()

methods, which use base jclass. Having APIs that use non-bare jclass

makes these methods hard to use.



Why not just use JavaRef<> instead of bare jclass? Because the

_clazz() use std::atomic to store them, and there is no

way to return a JavaRef<> from a jclass without going through

ScopedJavaLocalRef, which adds an unnecessary local ref.



The change:

1) Changes JavaRef in jni_array.cc to use bare jclass,

and updates all call sites to them as well.



When it was straight-forward, I updated call sites to use @JniType

instead of manual vector->array conversions.



This changes @JniType support in three ways:

1) Automatically add the template type for @JniType("std::vector")

(usually ScopedJavaLocalRef).

2) Add jni_zero::ConvertArray specialization for

ScopedJavaLocalRef.

3) When returning a typed array for a non-system type, pass the

Class object as the last parameter.

* This is a bit subtle, but it nice because it will allow R8 to

rename the class that is being used.

* We unfortunately cannot use this trick for @CalledByNative

parameters, so should likely emit a warning / error if

application array types are used in this context.



Bug: 324108033

entry.title: [//components/exo] Compute texture target to use from ClientSharedImage
entry.content:
exo::Buffer takes in a texture target to use and when in zero-copy mode,

passes it to a gpu::MailboxHolder that it creates. The only production

callsites that create exo::Buffer instances in zero-copy mode are at

[1] and [2] (the latter via [3][4]).



This CL changes exo::Buffer to compute the texture target from the

ClientSharedImage that was created from the passed-in GMB. This

function has identical semantics to what is currently being done, based

on the following reasoning:



* For [1], the texture target is currently being computed at [5]. This

is exactly what ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget(BufferFormat)

does.

* [2] is hardcoding the format to RGBA_8888. For RGBA_8888,

ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget(BufferFormat) will always return

GL_TEXTURE_2D on ChromeOS [6].



We leave a CHECK_EQ() for verification in going through trybots/CI. Once

this CL passes trybots/CI, we will remove exo::Buffer taking in a

texture

target altogether.

entry.title: [//gpu] Handle 2-fence case in AHBDawnImageRepresentation::EndAccess()
entry.content:
We currently DCHECK() that SharedTextureMemory::EndAccess() gives us

back 1 FD. However, that DCHECK is going off (see bug). On code

inspection, SharedTextureMemoryVk::EndAccessImpl() creates and gives

back 1 FD, while SharedTextureMemory::EndAccess() will add on the FD

that we gave in BeginAccess() if that FD wasn't consumed in a submit

(i.e., Dawn didn't touch the texture during the access).



This CL works around the bug by having

AHBDawnImageRepresentation::EndAccess() restore the fence that was

created in BeginAccess() in this case, as that is still the fence on

which the next access should wait. Once crbug.com/dawn/2454 is fixed,

this Chromium-side special-casing will no longer be necessary, as Dawn

will return the fence passed to it in BeginAccess() as the sole fence

in this case.

entry.title: Fix sandbox top navigation tests using external URLs.
entry.content:
The sandbox top navigation WPTs currently attempt a top-level navigation

to 'https://google.com'. Not only is using external URLs bad practice,

Firefox's test harness code refuses to make requests to remote URLs.

This causes these tests to crash in their trybots.



This CL updates the tests to point to the WPT-supported URL

'http://{{hosts[alt][www2]}}:{{ports[http][0]}}'. This is chosen so the

URL will be cross-site to the URLs the main page and the iframes will

be navigated to in the various tests.



See this comment on the WPT GitHub repo:

https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/35697#issuecomment-1970026245

entry.content:
Create a new EnterpriseLogoUrl policy.

Add logic in the BrowserManagementService to keep that latest version

of that image in memory. This service seems appropriate for this task

since it contains information about the profile management, and the

logo is another hint of the profile's manager.

is destroyed and reconstructed each time it is shown, therefore it

cannot hold the image.

Reading the image from an image cache leads to a delay in the image

being shown or a delay in the profile menu being shown.

Modify the ProfileMenuView to use that image as a badge if it is

available.

entry.title: [//gpu] Relax Metal/Graphite constraints in GLTextureImageBackingFactory
entry.content:
GLTextureImageBackingFactory currently disallows creations of

SharedImages in the following cases:



* ANGLE-Metal is being used and the client has specified GLES2 usage (as

in this case it is not guaranteed that WebGL will be using the same

GPU as raster)

* Graphite is being used and the client has specified raster usage (as

in this case it is not guaranteed that Skia is using GL)



However, there are special cases of these where it is safe to create

GLTextureImageBackings:



* For the former: When GLES2 is being used *only for raster*

* For the latter: When raster is being used *only over the GLES2

interface*



The client can specify that it is in one of these special cases via

the usages that it passes in.



This CL changes GLTextureImageBackingFactory to allow creation when

in these cases. We also add unittests verifying the new behavior of

GLTextureImageBackingFactory.

entry.title: [//components/exo] Remove exo::Buffer::Texture::texture_target_
entry.content:
This field is used only in Buffer::Texture::CopyTexImage(texture), where

it is the `texture_target_` field of `texture` that is used. The latter

is called only once in the codebase [1], wherein a Texture instance that

was created via the constructor that does not take in a GMB was passed

texture target on ChromeOS.

MailboxHolder for the SharedImage of the Texture in question here is in

fact already hardcoded to GL_TEXTURE_2D.

entry.title: [anchor] Remove CalculationExpressionAnchorQueryNode
entry.content:
As of CL:5355673, anchor/-size() functions resolve computed-value time,

which means that we don't need a CalculationExpressionNode for the

anchor functions anymore. This CL instead adds AnchorQuery, which is

used as the input for AnchorEvaluator::Evaluate.



Much of the data in AnchorItem (which is a key into a cache) has been

moved to AnchorQuery, such that AnchorItem can simply embed AnchorQuery

as a member. This eliminates the duplication we previously had between

AnchorItem and CalculationExpressionAnchorQueryNode. We also eliminate

some other back-and-forth conversion between AnchorItem and

CalculationExpressionAnchorQueryNode (e.g.

AnchorItem::ToExpressionNode).



Since AnchorQuery can be created without heap allocations, there's

probably no need anymore for g_anchor_top (etc) in InsetArea.



Note that there are no new unit tests for AnchorQuery in this CL,

because there's good coverage via unit tests for AnchorItem

(anchor_results_tests.cc).

entry.title: [UPM] Fix potential crash in BuiltInBackendToAndroidBackendMigrator
entry.content:
BuiltInBackendToAndroidBackendMigrator::RemoveBlacklistedFormsWithValues

currently doesn't wait for the passwords being actually removed from the

database. This may lead to a crash in this scenario:

- Migration continues without waiting for backend::RemoveLoginAsync to

finish.

- MigrationFinished gets called, metrics get reported and the metrics

reporter is reset.

- backend::RemoveLoginAsync finishes unsuccessfully (with an error) and

also calls MigrationFinished. The crash will happen because the metrics

reporter would be already reset at this point.



This CL ties the RemoveLoginAsync calls into the callback chain.

entry.title: Fix some more incompatibilities with std::variant from narrowing
entry.content:
std::variant does not allow narrowing conversions. absl::variant didn't

quite get this right, which means narrowing conversions sometimes sneak

in.



The main non-obvious consequence is that variant cannot be

constructed from literals like 0 or 2. Such literals have type int, and

an int may be negative. These ints will not be negative, but the

language has lost this information by the time it calls the std::variant

constructor. Writing 0u or 2u works because those have type unsigned,

which can convert to size_t without narrowing. In C++23, we'll have 0uz

and 2uz which even have type size_t, but we're not there yet and no

supported platform has unsigned larger than size_t.



Conversely, a variant cannot be constructed from a size_t

entry.title: Call HasInput() from Android message pump
entry.content:
Add base::android::InputHintChecker::HasInput() and call it from

message_pump_android.cc. Add a placeholder implementation and put it

behind a base::Feature.



This change covers all intentional modifications in //base/message_loop.

A working implementation (without tests) can be seen as a

work-in-progress change at crrev.com/c/5303439.



Since the input hint can only be fetched from the UI thread, only the

MessagePumpType::UI asks for it.



Design constraints that might not be obvious: the input hint cannot be

fetched at all times. It depends on:

1. asynchronous initialization (on a special background thread)

2. a weak reference to a View (java object) provided by Java layers



The (2) can even go away in multi-window mode. Subject to Java code to

be landed later.
